A <strong>class</strong> is a blueprint/template defining attributes and methods. An <strong>object</strong> is an instance of a class created at runtime. Example:<br><pre><code>class Car {
  String brand;
  int speed;
  void drive() { ... }
}
Car myCar = new Car(); // object</code></pre>

Evaluates an expression and executes the matching <code>case</code>. Each case ends with <code>break</code> to prevent fall-through. <code>default</code> handles unmatched values. Works with int, char, String, and enum.<br><pre><code>switch (day) {
  case 1: System.out.println("Mon"); break;
  case 2: System.out.println("Tue"); break;
  default: System.out.println("Other");
}</code></pre>

A class defines a new type. Fields store state; methods define behaviour. Objects are created with <code>new</code>:<br><pre><code>class Student {
  String name;    // instance field
  int age;

  void display() {
    System.out.println(name + " " + age);
  }
}
Student s = new Student();
s.name = "Alice";
s.display();</code></pre>

A <strong>constructor</strong> is a special method called when an object is created with <code>new</code>. It has the same name as the class and no return type. Used to initialise fields. Java provides a default no-arg constructor if none is defined.<br><pre><code>class Student {
  String name;
  int age;

  Student(String n, int a) { // parameterised constructor
    name = n;
    age = a;
  }
}
Student s = new Student("Alice", 20);</code></pre>

A <strong>subclass</strong> inherits fields and methods from a <strong>superclass</strong> using the <code>extends</code> keyword. The subclass can add new members and override inherited methods. Java does not support multiple class inheritance (a class can only extend one class) but supports multilevel and hierarchical inheritance.<br><pre><code>class Animal {
  String name;
  void eat() { System.out.println("eating"); }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
  void bark() { System.out.println("woof"); }
}
Dog d = new Dog();
d.eat();  // inherited
d.bark(); // own method</code></pre>

Best practice: declare all fields <code>private</code> and provide public getters/setters. This enforces encapsulation — internal state is hidden and only controlled access is allowed:<br><pre><code>class BankAccount {
  private double balance;

  public double getBalance() {
    return balance;
  }
  public void deposit(double amount) {
    if (amount > 0) balance += amount;
  }
}</code></pre>

An array is a fixed-size, ordered collection of elements of the same type. Creating an array in Java:<br><pre><code>// Declaration and creation
int[] marks = new int[5];   // array of 5 ints, default 0
marks[0] = 85;
marks[1] = 92;

// Declaration with initialisation
String[] names = {"Alice", "Bob", "Carol"};

// Array length
System.out.println(names.length); // 3</code></pre>

A 2D array is an array of arrays — represents a table or matrix:<br><pre><code>int[][] matrix = new int[3][4]; // 3 rows, 4 columns
matrix[0][0] = 1;

// Initialisation shorthand
int[][] grid = {
  {1, 2, 3},
  {4, 5, 6},
  {7, 8, 9}
};

// Iterating
for (int i = 0; i < grid.length; i++)
  for (int j = 0; j < grid[i].length; j++)
    System.out.print(grid[i][j]);</code></pre>

